To create a C program for the Raspberry Pi Zero W that uses a HC-SR501 PIR sensor connected to GPIO 17 and logs the state changes to a file named `motion.log`, you will need to use the `wiringPi` library. Below is a step-by-step guide and the complete code to achieve this.

### Step 1: Install `wiringPi`
First, ensure that you have the `wiringPi` library installed on your Raspberry Pi Zero W. You can install it via the following command:

```sh
git clone https://github.com/WiringPi/WiringPi.git
cd WiringPi
./build
```

### Step 2: Write the C Program

Here is a C program that reads from the HC-SR501 PIR sensor, logs the state changes to a file, and includes robust error handling for GPIO initialization.

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <wiringPi.h>

#define PIR_PIN 17
#define LOG_FILE "motion.log"

int main() {
    int fd;
    FILE *log_file;

    // Initialize wiringPi
    if (wiringPiSetup() == -1) {
        fprintf(stderr, "Error initializing wiringPi\n");
        return 1;
    }

    // Set up the PIR sensor pin as an input
    pinMode(PIR_PIN, INPUT);

    // Open the log file for appending
    log_file = fopen(LOG_FILE, "a");
    if (!log_file) {
        perror("Failed to open log file");
        return 1;
    }

    printf("Motion detection started.\n");

    while (1) {
        // Read the current state of the PIR sensor
        int state = digitalRead(PIR_PIN);

        // Log the state change with a timestamp
        time_t rawtime;
        struct tm *timeinfo;
        char buffer[80];
        time(&rawtime);
        timeinfo = localtime(&rawtime);

        strftime(buffer, sizeof(buffer), "%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S", timeinfo);
        fprintf(log_file, "%s PIR: %d\n", buffer, state);

        // Sleep for a short period before checking again
        delay(100); // 100 milliseconds
    }

    fclose(log_file);

    return 0;
}
```

